    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-08-14T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-08-14T22:00:00-05:00" n="996"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d996">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.111/451: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-15T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >August 15, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Reference Chungking’s telegram of February 15, 11 a.m., to Peiping in regard to
                    restrictions on travel of foreign nationals across Yellow River and flooded area
                    in Honan.</p>
                <p>In May and in August of this year the Embassy brought two applications of
                    Americans desiring to cross the Yellow River near Cheng-chow, Honan, to the
                    attention of the Foreign Office and requested that the applicants be granted
                    facilities for travel via that route. However, <pb facs="0904" n="896"
                        xml:id="pg_896"/> the Foreign Office refused these requests on the alleged
                    ground of military necessity and inability to grant adequate protection. The
                    Chinese military authorities are still strictly and uniformly prohibiting the
                    passage of foreign nationals via the various points within the closed line of
                    the Yellow River and the flooded area in Honan. The foregoing information should
                    be brought to the attention of American nationals who propose to travel via the
                    Honan route into the unoccupied provinces.</p>
                <p>Sent to Peiping, Tientsin, Chefoo, Tsingtao, Shanghai, Hankow. Repeated to
                    Department. Tsingtao please mail to Tsinanfu. Shanghai please mail to
                    Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
